## TL;DR: Cushion vs Radiant — The One-Sentence Answer

The cushion cut vs radiant cut diamond decision is primarily a silhouette choice, not a sparkle or price choice. Both cuts produce high-intensity brilliant-type sparkle. The difference is the shape: cushion has fully rounded, pillow-soft corners; radiant has beveled, truncated corners that give it a distinct octagonal outline.

**Contrarian Truth — The Corner Question:** Most buyers approach this comparison expecting a clear quality winner. There is none. A cushion modified brilliant and a radiant cut of equivalent grades look nearly identical in sparkle output and face-up presence — the only visible difference is the corner treatment: soft and round on the cushion, beveled and geometric on the radiant. Buyers who have never seen both side-by-side often cannot state a preference until they do.

**Live price snapshot at 1ct (Blue Nile {{year}}):**
- Cushion Modified — GIA G-VS1 Ideal: **[$1,891](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**
- Cushion Modified — GIA E-VS1 Ideal: **[$2,198](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/24436728?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**
- Radiant — IGI H-VS2 Very Good: **[$1,910](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26737014?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**
- Radiant — GIA E-VVS1 Ideal: **[$4,560](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28879187?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**

**→ The starting point** for most buyers: cushion at [GIA 1ct G-VS1 Ideal Modified, $1,891](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23740863?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — GIA certified, Ideal cut, reliably eye-clean VS1, lowest natural entry for quality cushion. Choose radiant only after seeing both side-by-side and consciously preferring the beveled corner silhouette.

---

## What Is the Cushion Cut vs Radiant Cut Difference?

The cushion cut vs radiant cut diamond comparison is one of the most misunderstood in the engagement ring market. Both cuts are brilliant-type (meaning they use brilliant-style facet arrangements to maximise light return), both are broadly "square or rectangular with softened edges," and both overlap in face-up size at equivalent carat weights. The difference is entirely in the corner geometry and what that means for the ring's silhouette from above.

I'm **Farzana Hasan**, a GIA Expert. The [cushion cut vs radiant cut](/cushion-cut-diamond) comparison matters most to buyers who have narrowed their search to fancy square cuts but are undecided between the cushion's soft romantic outline and the radiant's sharper geometric one. At identical quality grades and carat weights, the two cuts deliver a nearly identical sparkle experience.

The decision turns almost entirely on which corner treatment you prefer — which is why I always ask buyers to see both in a ring, on a hand, before committing.

This guide covers every dimension of the comparison: silhouette, sparkle, face-up size, price, elongation, setting compatibility, lab grown options, and the final verdict by buyer type. For the full cushion shape overview, see the [cushion cut diamond guide](/cushion-cut-diamond). For the full radiant shape overview, see the [radiant cut diamond guide](/radiant-cut-diamond).

---

## The Corner Question

The Corner Question defines the entire cushion vs radiant comparison: cushion cut diamonds have no corners at all — the edges curve continuously into soft, rounded points that give the cut its pillow-like name. Radiant cut diamonds have corners, but they are truncated: the 90-degree corner is cut away at a 45-degree angle, creating a small beveled flat — sometimes called a "cropped" or "clipped" corner. This is not the same as a princess cut's sharp 90-degree corner, which is the most fragile corner type in diamond cutting.

**Why The Corner Question matters in practice.** In a four-prong solitaire setting, the corner shape is fully visible from above. A cushion in four prongs looks like a rounded square pillow. A radiant in four prongs looks like a geometric octagon. Both are attractive, but they project completely different visual personalities — the cushion reads as romantic and organic; the radiant reads as architectural and modern. In a bezel setting, both the cushion's rounds and the radiant's bevels are enclosed in metal and the difference is partially hidden. In a halo setting, the halo's own shape — usually circular or cushion-shaped — frames both cuts similarly, making the original corner treatment nearly invisible from above.

**The Corner Question and durability.** Cushion cuts have no structural vulnerability at the corners — the continuous curve has no stress point. Radiant cuts have small beveled corners that are structurally stronger than princess cut's sharp 90-degree corners, but slightly more vulnerable than the cushion's fully rounded curve. In practice, radiant corner vulnerability is negligible in a four-prong setting where all four beveled corners are protected — the comparison matters only if the buyer prefers a bezel-free setting and has an active lifestyle with high ring-contact activity.

![The Corner Question: cushion vs radiant cut silhouette comparison infographic showing rounded vs beveled corners, face-up area, and setting compatibility](/images/cushion-vs-radiant-corner-question.avif)

**Answering The Corner Question.** Ask yourself: does a soft, pillow outline or a beveled, geometric outline better match the aesthetic of the other jewellery you wear? If the answer is soft and organic, the cushion is correct. If the answer is angular and architectural, the radiant is correct. If you genuinely cannot decide, view both cuts in person before purchasing.

---

## The Elongation Divide

Both cushion and radiant cuts are available in elongated versions — length-to-width ratios above 1.10 for cushion and above 1.25 for radiant — but the elongated forms look fundamentally different despite the shared goal of finger-elongating visual effect.

**Elongated cushion.** An elongated cushion cut (LW ratio 1.10–1.25) stretches the pillow outline along one axis. The result is a rectangle with fully soft, rounded corners — the shape retains the cushion's organic, pillow-like character at every proportion. At 1.15–1.20 LW, the elongated cushion reads as a longer version of a square cushion from above; at 1.25, it begins to look like a shorter oval. For the full elongated cushion analysis, see the [elongated cushion cut diamond guide](/elongated-cushion-cut-diamond).

**Elongated radiant.** An elongated radiant cut (LW ratio 1.25–1.50) stretches the octagonal outline along one axis. The result is a rectangle with beveled corners — the shape has a distinctly architectural, linear character. At 1.30–1.35 LW, the elongated radiant reads as a horizontal bar of sparkle with geometric precision. East-west ring settings (stone set horizontally across the finger rather than vertically) are particularly associated with the elongated radiant, because the rectangular shape with beveled corners creates a bold, modern visual at that orientation.

![The Elongation Divide: elongated cushion 1.20 LW vs elongated radiant 1.30 LW comparison infographic showing soft pillow vs geometric rectangle character at 2ct](/images/cushion-vs-radiant-elongation-divide.avif)

**Where The Elongation Divide is most visible.** Place an elongated cushion (1.20 LW) next to an elongated radiant (1.30 LW) in the same carat weight. The cushion looks like a soft, romantic elongated pillow. The radiant looks like a precise, modern geometric rectangle. Most buyers who prefer the elongated shape have a strong preference between these two characters — the Elongation Divide is clearer at elongated proportions than it is in the square comparison, where both cuts read similarly from a distance.

**Face-up coverage.** At the same carat weight, elongated versions of both cuts face up larger than square versions, because the elongated shape distributes more of the diamond's weight across the finger rather than concentrating it in depth. Between the two elongated forms at the same carat and LW ratio, the elongated radiant tends to face up marginally larger than the elongated cushion because radiants typically carry less weight in the crown and more at the girdle.

