## Sparkle: Cushion Modified Brilliant vs Radiant

Both the cushion modified brilliant and the radiant cut use brilliant-type faceting — the same class of facet arrangement that produces the round brilliant's renowned light return. Both deliver high levels of scintillation (the on/off flashing of white and coloured light as the stone and viewer move) and both show fire (rainbow colour dispersion). The practical question is whether the sparkle character is meaningfully different between the two.

**Cushion modified brilliant sparkle.** The cushion modified brilliant's additional pavilion facets break the stone's light return into many small, uniform reflections — the "crushed ice" texture. The pattern reads as continuous, fine, high-density sparkle with no dominant individual flash zones. This is the sub-type that dominates Blue Nile's cushion inventory.

**Radiant cut sparkle.** The radiant cut's 70-facet design produces a sparkle pattern that is similar to the cushion modified brilliant but with more directional flash zones — the rectangular or square face-up shows both the crushed ice character across the stone's body and larger individual flash zones near the corners. Many buyers describe the radiant as "more fiery" than the cushion modified brilliant, which is accurate — the radiant's corner facets produce more visible rainbow colour dispersion.

**Cushion brilliant vs radiant.** The cushion brilliant sub-type (larger, chunkier facets) produces a distinctly different sparkle from the cushion modified brilliant — more similar to the radiant in its larger flash zones and more visible fire. Buyers who prefer the radiant's sparkle character over the cushion modified brilliant should consider whether the cushion brilliant sub-type meets their sparkle preference without the radiant's corner geometry. The GIA or IGI certificate's "Shape and Cutting Style" field identifies which cushion sub-type a specific stone is.

