## Lab Grown Comparison: Cushion vs Radiant

In the lab grown market, the price difference between cushion modified brilliants and radiant cuts largely disappears. Lab production costs do not have the inventory imbalance that creates the natural cushion discount — both shapes are produced in similar volumes, and the price per carat reflects quality grades rather than shape demand premium.

**Lab cushion pricing at 1.5ct.** The [IGI 1.5ct E-VVS2 Excellent Cushion Modified Lab at $1,422](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28961887?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the value benchmark for lab cushion buyers at the 1.5ct tier. A lab radiant at 1.5ct of equivalent quality (E-VVS2 Excellent) runs $1,400–$1,600 — within $200 of the cushion equivalent. The shape choice in lab is a pure aesthetic decision: there is no meaningful financial advantage to either shape.

**Lab vs natural: same comparison applies.** A lab radiant and a lab cushion of identical grades are physically and optically identical to their natural counterparts — same 70-facet brilliance, same corner geometry, same face-up size. The sparkle difference between lab cushion modified brilliant and lab radiant is identical to the natural comparison: both deliver brilliant-type sparkle; the radiant shows marginally more fire at the corners; the cushion modified brilliant shows more uniform crushed ice. The corner geometry — The Corner Question — remains the central decision in lab as it is in natural.

> "In the lab market, I tell buyers to make the cushion vs radiant decision purely on visual preference — not on price, not on availability, and not on any assumption that one is 'better' than the other. They are nearly identical in price, nearly identical in sparkle, and available at equivalent quality grades. The only question is: which corner treatment do you want to see on your hand for the next fifty years?" — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

---

## Face-Up Size: Cushion vs Radiant

At the same carat weight and similar length-to-width ratios, cushion and radiant cuts face up at nearly identical dimensions. Both shapes distribute their carat weight similarly across the face-up area — neither cut carries significantly more weight in the crown or pavilion relative to the other.

**At 1ct.** A 1ct square cushion is approximately 6.5mm × 6.5mm face-up. A 1ct square radiant is approximately 5.5mm × 5.5mm, because the radiant's beveled corners remove four small triangles of visible face-up area that the cushion's rounded corners retain. This makes the cushion appear marginally larger than the radiant at the same carat weight — the continuous curve captures more visual face-up area than the clipped corner.

**At 2ct and above.** The face-up size advantage of the cushion over the radiant at the same carat weight is most visible in square proportions. At elongated proportions (1.20+ LW), the difference reverses slightly — the radiant's corner clips in the elongated orientation do not reduce as much face-up area proportionally, and the radiant can appear marginally larger per carat than the elongated cushion. For carat-weight-to-face-up comparisons at each size tier, the [cushion cut diamond guide](/cushion-cut-diamond) has full mm dimensions.

---

## Settings: Which Cut Works Better?

Both cushion and radiant cuts are compatible with every major engagement ring setting type. The setting choice interaction is slightly different between the two cuts due to The Corner Question.

**Four-prong solitaire.** Both cuts look excellent in four-prong settings. The cushion's rounded corners look natural in a four-prong claw — the prong sits at the corner curve naturally. The radiant's beveled corners create a specific design requirement: prongs must be placed at the beveled corner flat rather than at a point, so the setting must account for the radiant's octagonal geometry. Most standard settings accommodate both, but confirm with the retailer for radiant cuts in vintage or custom prong settings.

**Halo.** Both cuts are excellent halo candidates. In a cushion halo, the outer row of pavé follows the cushion's rounded profile and the stone fills the setting naturally. In a radiant halo, the halo follows either a square/octagonal path that mirrors the radiant's geometry or a rounded path that softens the radiant's corners. A cushion-profile halo on a radiant creates the visual effect of a cushion with the radiant's interior sparkle — a popular hybrid look.

**Bezel.** Both cuts can be set in bezel settings. The cushion bezel creates a continuous metal band around the soft, rounded perimeter — clean and modern. The radiant bezel must accommodate the beveled corners, creating a slightly more angular metal outline. Both look excellent; the choice is whether the buyer wants a round-edged metal frame (cushion) or a geometric-edged metal frame (radiant).

**Vintage / milgrain.** Both cuts pair well with vintage-style settings. Cushion cuts have historical precedent with vintage designs — the cut's origins in Old Mine Cut and Old European Cut make it a natural pairing with Victorian and Edwardian milgrain. Radiant cuts are more modern (the cut was developed in the 1970s) and look better in contemporary vintage-inspired designs than in true historical reproductions.

